V-P-C endpoints and PrivateLink.

A V-P-C Endpoint lets a V-P-C reach AWS services privately, without routing through an Internet Gateway, a N-A-T Gateway, or a V-P-N. It matters for two reasons: N-A-T bandwidth and per-gigabyte charges add up at scale, and many regulated workloads can't have traffic to AWS leave the AWS network at all. Two endpoint types tell the whole story. A Gateway Endpoint serves S3 and DynamoDB only, it's free, and it works by adding a route to a prefix list in your route tables. An Interface Endpoint, powered by PrivateLink, serves most AWS services, works by creating an E-N-I with a private I-P in your subnet, costs per hour plus per gigabyte, and optionally enables private D-N-S so the service's normal hostname resolves to that E-N-I. The rule: use a Gateway Endpoint for S3 and DynamoDB, since it's free, and an Interface Endpoint for everything else.

PrivateLink turns that same machinery around to expose your own service to other V-P-Cs, with no peering, no internet, and no C-I-D-R-overlap worry. The provider puts a Network Load Balancer in front of the service and creates a V-P-C Endpoint Service that registers it. Consumers create an Interface Endpoint targeting that service, and traffic flows privately over the backbone, from the consumer's private I-P to the provider's N-L-B. It's how SaaS vendors give thousands of customer V-P-Cs a private connection, and how internal microservices are shared across accounts.
